his that is as direct, but I mean this in the most friendly way possible: get over the archer envy and you will have more fun.  They are overpowered, they may get nerfed and they may not; if you both want to be an assassin, and want to play DAoC, you need to accept that and be comfortable with it. If you can’t, you are either playing the wrong class or the wrong game, and unless you change one or the other you will continue being unhappy unless archers get nerfed and/or assassins get a huge boost, neither of which is a guarantee.<br><br>Perhaps this is a powergamer mentality, but when I start playing a game, I find out what the rules are and play by them in such a way that best achieves my goals (and if the rules change, which they do frequently in MMOGs, I adapt).  I’ve noticed a very common attitude in MMOGs of trying to change the rules so they fit your idea of what they should be.  Most of the time you will fail, and even if you succeed, chances are someone else’s idea of what the rules should be was totally different (or worse, what it used to be before your petitioned change!).<br><br>There was a similar issue with my class in EQ: Shadowknight.  SKs were perennially underpowered, though we had a combination of abilities such that the more clever/skilled SKs were quite powerful in ways Verant probably did not intend.  There seemed to be two distinct camps: those that absolutely loved the class (and usually recognized that there were, in fact, glaring problems), and those that were eternally dissatisfied and either screamed constantly for changes, or were Prophets of Doom that did nothing but talk about how terrible the class is and how much more fun they’re having with their Warrior.  I see that here. I came to define the two thusly, and here I change back to DAoC: you either &quot;play&quot; an assassin, or you <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> are</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> an assassin.  I could write a post as long as Ela’s reports on the difference, but I’