ncies of Critical Srike as a specialization. <br><br>For those that have a hard time understanding the soft gimp of the Melee Archer vs the Hard gimp of the Assassin, I'll relate things in different words. Anything in brackets shows their parallel. <br><br><br>Imagine there was a new class in Hibernia called &quot;Shieldbearer&quot; [Assassin] <br><br>They can only wear Reinforced instead of Hero's Scale [Leather], but are still expected to take the brunt of attacks. <br><br>They get Evade III instead of Evade I of Heroes [Evade III vs Evade VII] <br><br>They CANNOT specialize in 2-h weapons [Bows] <br><br>They CAN specialize in &quot;Shieldbearing&quot; [Critical Strike] <br><br>To entice them to take up the Shieldbearing specialization, Parry has been removed [Pathfinding/Beastcraft]. <br><br>Shieldbearing DOES NOT add any chance to block with the shield, only the original Shield Specialization does. Instead, it adds a few Shield Styles and some Shield Chains to supplement damage, and these Chains are only executed at the beginning of combat. The first chain introduced at low levels can only be executed in melee if you block the first strike in combat. It is soon overridden by a second chain, and even a third 3-chain that only can be initiated in the first hit in combat IF you block the first hit from the opponent (generally 40% chance to block that hit) [Perf Artery] <br><br>The rest of the Shieldbearing styles hit with the shield with positional styles much like the same way weapon specialization would do anyway. <br><br>Shieldbearers have a &quot;Damage Sense&quot; ability where a warning message appears when a Warrior or Armsman is in visible range. <br><br>Shieldbearers have no 30 min timer &quot;get out of jail&quot; wildcard like the Heroes have with Stag form [Archer speed shout] <br><br><br><br>After a class with this setup is introduced, the question remains, are Heroes better with a Shield Specialized setup (soft gimp) than a Shieldbearer's Best Shield setup (hard gimp)? <br><br>SHIELD SPECIALIZED HERO: <br>+ Heroes wear Scale (better absorb) <br>+ Heroes have Parry (30% chance parry) <br>+ Heroes have Stag Form when in danger (+45% hp) <br><br>SHIELDBEARER: <br>+ Has Evade III (better evade) <br>+ Has more styles to choose from <br>+ Detect Warrior/Armsman <br><br>&quot;Why would I play a shield bearing Hero [melee Archer] if I wanted to be offensive minded? I would rather roll a 2-h or Spear Hero [Bow Archer]&quot; <br><br>This has nothing to do with Hero Nerfs in relation to Shields, rather it has to do with improving Shieldbearer's defensive ability to surpass that of Heros. <br><br>============================================<br><br>Both Weapon and Dual Wield have built in diminishing return factors to counter the lost gains from spending many more points in the specialization for the same gain. Critical Strike has no diminishing returns factor, because there is no benefit to specializing it other than styles. <br><br>Weapon Specialization after 2/3 max (level 33 spec at 50) gains twice as much benefit per point level. <br><br>Dual Wield after level 20 gains twice as much benefit per point level. <br><br>Critical Strike = none <br><br><br>At Level 50: <br><br>50 Weapon Specialization = +66% casual damage output <br>50 Dual Wield = +32% casual damage output <br>50 Critical Strike = +0% casual damage output <br><br>Weapon specialization provides the most gains in casual melee, of course though, it is weapon type specific so it should remain where it is at. <br><br>Dual Wield is an example of a specialization that adds more styles to the arsenal light Critical Strike does. It is victim to some cross-skill redundancy, but it also adds up to a +32% boost to casual melee damage output in all situations compared to minimum specialization. This works very well for Light Tanks, and the skill applies to any weapon, hence it is weaker than weapon spec itself. <br><br>Critical Strike suffers from both cross and inter-skill redundancy. Like Dual Wield, an Assassin with Critical Strike will have overlapping styles. It is made worse if the Assassin has also specialized in Dual Wield. What is even worse is that Critical Strike will override it's own styles through redundancy. On top of this, there is no casual melee damage output that is useful in all situations. An Assassin nearly Voids an entire specialization line upon being revealed, or after that first strike in combat. <br><br><br>If we use Dual Wield as an example of a good specialization that increases damage output in casual melee and adds styles and offers only cross-redundant styles, Critical Strike could use the same kind of scaling factor, in that it has even more redundant style factors, but their Perforate they can pull off is their defining skill. <br><br>If Dual Wield at full specialization increases the chance to hit from 25% to 65% (a 32% boost to overall damage), what equation can Critical Strike use to simulate a 32% boost to overall damage. <br><br>The chance to casually Critical HIT in combat is 10%, thus increasing overall casual melee damage by 10% <br><br>If Critical Strike applied to Critical Hits in casual melee (something I thought was factored in when I start the game), you can multiply the 1.32 Full Spec factor by 1.10 Base Critical Hit factor and you get a final percentage of 45.2%. <br><br>Our goal now is to find an equation that will get an Assassin a chance to Critical Hit from 10% to 45.2% <br><br>If Until Level 30, Assassins receive +.5% to Critical Strike with 30 specialization, that adds to the Critical Hit factor: <br><br>10%(base) + (Level 30 / 2)% = 25% <br><br>Beyond Level 30, the equation shifts to compensate for diminishing returns like Weapon Spec does at 2/3 and Dual Wield does at level 20+, so that there is a 1% gain after each CS level after 30. <br><br>The 20 Levels between 30 and 50 add 20% <br><br>Add that 20% + the 25% from levels 1-30, and you get: <br><br>45% <br><br>Which reaches our goal of 45.2% <br><br>That 10% to 45% increase in Critical Hit increases damage output by 32% much the same way Dual Wield does at full spec. <br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=ela>Ela</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/1/02 8:56:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1983.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ela’s Assassin Volume IV 1/2</span><hr size=1> A reply to another post regarding melee Ranger vs Assassin:<br><br>===========================================<br><br>ealaniel: <br><br>As you pointed out ealaniel, Evade and Absorption alone shows that Nightshades receive 14% less damage. <br><br>DEFENSE: <br><br>- Nightshades receive 14% less damage through Evasion vs Ranger Absorbtion. <br><br>+? Ranger Qui Buff add to Evade? <br>+ Ranger Self AF Buff <br>+ Ranger Dex Buff increases Defense <br><br>* The Quickness affecting Evade wasn't included in the original example because it has not been verified, but I seem to evade more often with a Dex/Qui buff from a Druid vs a regular Dex Buff. When I ran tests when I was around level 32, a combination of both Dex and Dex/Qui druid buffs from a full specialized Nurture Druid decreased damage from 80 to 60. Combine that with the Ranger Self AF Buff and that should overcome the base 14% advantage that the Nightshade has. <br><br>OFFENSE: <br><br>+ Rangers Attack Faster with Qui Buff. <br>+ Rangers Receive Damage bonus from Str Buff. <br>+ Rangers Receive Damage bonus from Dex Buff. <br><br>- Cannot supplement a one time DoT or Debuff <br>(38 damage tick x 5 = 190 damage over 20 seconds) <br><br>+ Rangers do get a (9.4 DPS) damage add buff. Over the course of 5 seconds, that adds up to 47 damage (235 damage over 20 seconds), compared to the 38 damage DoT. That alone over the course is enough to do more damage over time than the Poison Dot. Rangers can miss, but Nightshades can both miss landing the poison and have it resisted completely. <br><br>* The Ranger Damage Add alone defeats poison (so much for Envenom). The rest of the buffs add to damage as well. <br><br><br>&gt;&quot;True, but to what extent. Anyone with level 12 bow skill actually tried to shoot anything level 50? I'm thinking that this may not work as well as you think.&quot; <br><br>I never meant to say it works well, this is a Melee Ranger afterall. It was to show that the Melee Ranger has superior Melee and has an extra tool at Range still superior than what an Assassin can ever accomplish. <br><br>The point of showing the autotrain in bows is not to suggest they are powerful, but to show Archers still have some kind of bow ability (albiet weaker) that is superior to anything an Assassin can accomplish, where the reverse can't be said if an Assassin wanted to specialize in range attack and still be better than the Archer at Melee. <br><br><br>&gt;&gt;&quot;To actually *prove* that assassins were gimped vs melee archers you'd need to do an actual *test* for that, something that Ela has never bothered to do.&quot; <br><br>If you can find an Assassin with that setup at level 50 and a Melee Hunter/Ranger of level 50 and they're not in the same realm, I would be glad to see a test set up. It's not something that I can be &quot;bothered&quot; to do, I can't whip up a level 50 melee Archer in another realm to test it out with a flick of my finger, but Mythic can. I'm a gamer that has to follow the rules, I can't set up something like that out of the blue, that's why I'd request it on Pendragon.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 widt